title: Make CTRL+C finally work in the web and minor tweaks
Add the << and >> bit shift operators
Split the lang documentation in HELP and add some color
Add issue references for GOTO and ON ERROR
body:
Fixes #121.
Fixes #153.

title: Add a rudimentary bytecode representation and a compiler
Add support to interrupt execution via CTRL+C
Move the SDL main loop to a separate thread
Misc small changes during my SEA-JFK flight
Fix PRINT to support avoiding newline characters
body: If the PRINT statement ends in a comma or semicolon, do not print a newline character -- just like other BASICs do.

title: Support AS as an arg separator and use it in MOUNT
body: Looking through the QuickBASIC documentation, I found out that the command to rename a file is of the form "NAME old AS new".  Even though we don't have a rename command yet, we can start supporting AS as an argument separator and use it to make the MOUNT command more readable.

title: Add integer to/from double automatic promotion
Add exponents
body: This is the counterpart to the addition of the SQR function.  It's unfortunate that SQR is a function and exponents are an operator, because the former now lives in the std crate and the latter in core.

title: Track lines and columns in error messages
Fix insertion of newlines in the editor
body: Attempting to split the last line immediately after insertion did not work correctly due to an off-by-one problem, and inserting a newline at the end of an existing line did not work for similar reasons.  Add tests and then fix the problem.

title: Add basic support for labels and GOTO
Fix UTF-8 handling in input methods
body:
This is a the same as #162 from @zenria after resolving conflicts, reordering and squashing some commits, and ensuring the web interface works. I've tried to keep the original sequence of commits as much as possible. The original PR description reads:

Here is a summary of what has been done:

* Use a dedicated struct to manipulate string (LineBuffer) to avoid splitting inside UTF-8 code points.
* Console::write does not take bytes anymore but a string slice to ensure proper UTF-8 data is sent to the console.
* sdl & web implementation of write_wrapped do not manipulate bytes anymore but are using LineBuffer instead. This ensures correct line length & line splitting while wrapping.
* sdl console rendering use the render method instead of the render_latin1 method to properly render UTF-8 strings.

Fixes #161.

title: Parameterize the exec URL of the REPL
body:
This modifies the SHARE command so that the exec URL for public scripts
is configurable.  The cli always passes a fixed value, but this allows
the web UI to properly display its own origin.

title: Add auto-run support from URL
body:
This extends the web UI to recognize a "run" query parameter of the
form username/path which causes the interpreter to auto-load and run
the requested program.

title: Add the LOGOUT command
body:
This new command logs the user out of their current session and permits
lifting a longstanding limitation that prevented using LOGIN more than
once from the same interpreter.

title: Allow accessing public files without LOGIN
Revamp logins and signups to adapt to the new AAD-less cloud service
Add new client crate and parameterize service URL
Release EndBASIC 0.8.1
body:
Minor release to ship a couple of important usability fixes and to
migrate away from Google Analytics.

title: Fix read_line to properly clear old characters
body:
The old logic to clear the previous line assumed that the cursor was at the
end of the line that had to be cleared, which means we left characters behind
when the cursor was not at the end.  Fix that now and add a test.

Fixes #148.

title: Fix handling of keys that are browser shortcuts
body:
There are a bunch of key presses that should be recognized by EndBASIC
but that are also recognized by the browser.  Some include the Tab key,
the arrow keys (when "caret browsing" is enabled), and the slash key
in Firefox.

Before, pressing any of these keys would cause the browser to also
perform their default action, which meant that the REPL would misbehave
by losing focus or triggering links.  With this change, we prevent the
events from propagating to the browser once we have handled them so
that this problem doesn't surface.

This change is inspired by the fix submitted by @Protowalker in #140.

Fixes #136.

title: Post-release version bump and build fixes
Release EndBASIC 0.8.0
body:
As part of this change, tweak the release process slightly and update
the front page notes to highlight the new features.

title: Add support for page up/down in the editor
Misc improvements for the web UI
Reimplement the web UI using a custom canvas
Track the name of the program being edited and modifications to it
Extend CLEAR and NEW to reset machine state
Fix and test the SDL console
Fix build with Rust 1.55 and misc changes
Miscellaneous prework to support cloud drives
body: My local branch is going too big and hard to manage, so start merging some of the preliminary work to support cloud drives.

title: Add input history tracking to the REPL
body:
This is a long-time needed feature to make it less painful to interact
with the console, especially now that we have gained more complex file
system manipulation commands.

title: Add basic GPIO support for the Raspberry Pi
Replace END WHILE with WEND
body:
This is a gratuitous change, yes, and is primarily driven by the fact that
END WHILE isn't being recognized by syntax highlighters in all cases.
Plus this better matches the retro feeling I'm trying to achieve in this
project.

The very early implementation of EndBASIC had WEND...  but I replaced it
with END WHILE to remain consistent with END IF.  I did not notice at the
time that FOR would require NEXT instead and that no BASIC I can see has
END FOR (not even Visual Basic, which has a very rich END statement).

title: Readd the LIST command
body:
I've been missing this when showing screenshots of EndBASIC because,
without this command, it's not possible to show both a snippet of
code and its output at once.

title: Fix build with Rust 1.42
body:
This Rust release still ships with some systems (Raspbian in particular)
so make sure we can build against it.

title: Start cleaning up the mess arrays caused by improving the Symbols abstraction
Generalize and make tests more readable with a new Tester facility
Big reorganization
body: Make the REPL be part of `cli`, reuse that for the `web`, reshuffle integration tests, and move the standard library to a new `std` crate.

title: Start code reorganization
body: Most of these changes are in preparation for a split between the core of the language and the standard library. But as I think on how to do those best (because I hit some roadblocks with test utilities), these fixes and clean ups can go in on their own.
